      "acceptanceCriteria": "SQA plan documented; version control and regression testing in place for all simulation software components.",
      "rationale": "Ansys Mechanical 2022 R2 is used under a validated, version-controlled installation. An SQA plan covering software installation qualification, regression test suite execution, and change-control procedures is maintained by the simulation team. All three FEA codes (FDA, Ansys, DePuy Synthes internal) passed internal regression benchmarks prior to study execution."
    },
    {
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "factorType": "Numerical code verification",
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "requiredLevel": 2,
      "achievedLevel": 2,
      "acceptanceCriteria": "Code verification against analytical solutions or published benchmarks for linear elastic beam bending and contact mechanics.",
      "rationale": "Each FEA code was verified against NAFEMS benchmark LE1 (plane stress) and a cantilever beam analytical solution. Contact formulation was verified using a Hertzian contact reference case. All results agreed within 1% of analytical values, satisfying the required verification level."
    },
    {
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "factorType": "Discretization error",
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "requiredLevel": 2,
      "achievedLevel": 3,
      "acceptanceCriteria": "Mesh convergence study demonstrating <5% change in QoIs between successive refinements; Richardson extrapolation applied.",
      "rationale": "A three-level mesh refinement study was performed on the pedicle screw shank and rod-clamp interface regions. Richardson extrapolation yielded a GCI of 1.8% for peak von Mises stress and <0.5% for global stiffness. The production mesh (≈420,000 elements, predominantly C3D8R with enhanced hourglass control) was selected at the convergence plateau."
    },
    {
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "factorType": "Numerical solver error",
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "requiredLevel": 1,
      "achievedLevel": 2,
      "acceptanceCriteria": "Solver residual tolerances documented; equilibrium convergence confirmed for each load step.",
      "rationale": "Implicit quasi-static analyses were run with force and displacement residual tolerances of 1×10⁻⁴. Energy balance was monitored throughout each load step. No convergence warnings were recorded across the 11 simulated constructs. Solver error contribution to total numerical uncertainty is estimated at <0.1% of QoI."
    },
    {
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "factorType": "Use error",
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "requiredLevel": 2,
      "achievedLevel": 2,
      "acceptanceCriteria": "Simulation execution checklist followed; independent peer review of model setup by second analyst.",
      "rationale": "A documented simulation execution checklist (boundary conditions, material assignments, contact definitions, load application) was completed for each construct simulation. An independent analyst reviewed all model setup files prior to run submission. No use errors were identified during review."
    },
    {
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "factorType": "Model form",
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "requiredLevel": 3,
      "achievedLevel": 3,
      "acceptanceCriteria": "Model form assumptions (linear elasticity, small-strain plasticity, frictional contact) justified by physical reasoning and sensitivity analysis.",
      "rationale": "The construct operates in a regime where titanium alloy (Ti-6Al-4V) exhibits rate-independent elastic-plastic behavior. Bilinear isotropic hardening was adopted based on published tensile coupon data. Frictional contact (μ=0.3) at the screw-rod interface was justified by prior tribological measurements. A sensitivity study showed that ±20% variation in friction coefficient changes predicted yield force by <3%, within QoI uncertainty bounds."
    },
    {
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "factorType": "Model inputs",
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "requiredLevel": 3,
      "achievedLevel": 3,
      "acceptanceCriteria": "Material properties sourced from traceable coupon tests; geometric inputs from CMM measurements of production screws.",
      "rationale": "Ti-6Al-4V elastic modulus (114 GPa), yield strength (880 MPa), and tangent modulus (2.1 GPa) were obtained from tensile coupon tests on material from the same production lot as the test constructs. Screw geometry was characterised by CMM measurement of five representative screws; dimensional variability was propagated through a Monte Carlo analysis confirming <2% QoI sensitivity."
    },
    {
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "factorType": "Test samples",
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "requiredLevel": 2,
      "achievedLevel": 2,
      "acceptanceCriteria": "N≥10 constructs from production lot; traceability of samples to FEA geometry confirmed.",
      "rationale": "Eleven constructs were assembled from a single production lot of 7.5 mm non-cannulated pedicle screws and 5.5 mm titanium rods. Lot traceability records confirm dimensional conformance to design drawings used for FEA geometry. Sample size exceeds the pre-specified minimum of N=10."
    },
    {
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "factorType": "Test conditions",
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "requiredLevel": 3,
      "achievedLevel": 2,
      "acceptanceCriteria": "Test conditions span at least two loading rates and two fixturing configurations to bound the COU loading environment.",
      "rationale": "Testing was conducted exclusively under the standard ASTM F1717 quasi-static protocol at a single crosshead displacement rate (5 mm/min). A second loading rate or alternative fixturing configuration was not evaluated. This factor does not achieve the required level; the gap is accepted because the COU is explicitly limited to quasi-static ASTM F1717 conditions and the single-condition dataset is consistent with regulatory precedent for this device class."
    },
    {
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "factorType": "Equivalency of input parameters",
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "factorStatus": "not-assessed",
      "acceptanceCriteria": "Demonstration that FEA input parameters (material properties, geometry, boundary conditions) are equivalent to those present in the physical test specimens.",
      "rationale": "Equivalency of input parameters was not formally assessed because the assessment team determined that the direct traceability of material coupons and CMM geometry to the test lot renders a separate equivalency evaluation redundant for this COU. The factor is considered inapplicable given the single-lot, single-geometry study design; however, no formal scoping or inapplicability determination was documented in the credibility plan, and factorStatus has been left as not-assessed rather than not-applicable."
    },
    {
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "factorType": "Output comparison",
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "requiredLevel": 3,
      "achievedLevel": 4,
      "acceptanceCriteria": "Quantitative comparison metric (E/uval) applied to all three QoIs; pass/fail threshold pre-specified at E/uval < 1.96.",
      "rationale": "The validation metric E/uval was computed for stiffness (0.82), yield force (1.14), and force at 40 mm (0.97). All values are below the pre-specified threshold of 1.96. Mean percentage differences are 3.1%, 4.7%, and 2.9% respectively, all within the <10% acceptance criterion. Results are consistent across both laboratories."
    },
    {
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "factorType": "Relevance of the quantities of interest",
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "requiredLevel": 3,
      "achievedLevel": 3,
      "acceptanceCriteria": "QoIs directly map to regulatory submission endpoints and clinical failure modes.",
      "rationale": "Construct stiffness, yield force, and force at 40 mm displacement are the three QoIs specified in ASTM F1717 and referenced in FDA guidance for spinal implant 510(k) submissions. Each QoI corresponds to a clinically relevant failure mode: excessive flexibility (stiffness), permanent deformation onset (yield force), and ultimate load-bearing capacity (force at 40 mm). Relevance is high."
    },
    {
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "factorType": "Relevance of the validation activities to the COU",
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "requiredLevel": 3,
      "achievedLevel": 3,
      "acceptanceCriteria": "Validation activities replicate the COU geometry, loading, and boundary conditions with documented similarity arguments.",
      "rationale": "The validation constructs use the identical screw design, rod diameter, and UHMWPE block fixture specified in ASTM F1717, matching the COU loading scenario. Similarity arguments are documented in the validation plan: same material lot, same assembly torque, same test machine compliance. No extrapolation beyond the validated configuration is claimed."
    }
